2 HOUSE BILL 1306
1 Article – Health – General
2 10–6A–02.
3 (b) This subtitle may not be construed to abridge or modify any civil right of the
4 respondent, including:
5 (1) Any civil service ranking or appointment;
6 (2) The right to apply for voluntary admission to a facility under § 10–609
7 of this title; and
8 (3) [Any] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN §§ 5–133 AND 5–205 OF THE
9 PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE AND THE PROVISIONS OF THIS SUBTITLE RELATING TO A
10 COURT’S ORDER PROHIBITING POSSESSION OF A FIREARM, ANY right relating to a
11 license, permit, certification, privilege, or benefit under any law.
12 10–6A–08.
13 (a) If, after hearing all relevant evidence, the court does not find by clear and
14 convincing evidence that the respondent meets the criteria for assisted outpatient
15 treatment, the court shall deny the petition.
16 (b) (1) If, after hearing all relevant evidence, the court finds by clear and
17 convincing evidence that the respondent meets the criteria for assisted outpatient
18 treatment, the court shall order the respondent to comply with assisted outpatient
19 treatment for a period not to exceed 1 year.
20 (2) The order of the court shall incorporate a treatment plan that:
21 (i) Is limited in scope to the elements included in the treatment plan
22 presented to the court under § 10–6A–06 of this subtitle; and
23 (ii) Includes only those elements that the court finds by clear and
24 convincing evidence to be essential to the maintenance of the respondent’s health or safety.
25 10–6A–08.1.
26 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “FIREARM” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 5–101 OF
27 THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE.
28 (B) (1) IF A COURT ORDERS A RESPONDENT TO COMPLY WITH ASSISTED
29 OUTPATIENT TREATMENT UNDER § 10–6A–08 OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE COURT SHALL
30 MAKE A DETERMINATION AS TO WHETHER THE RESPONDENT IS LIKELY TO

HOUSE BILL 1306 3
1 ENDANGER OR CAUSE PHYSICAL INJURY TO THE RESPONDENT OR ANOTHER IF THE
2 RESPONDENT HAS ACCESS TO A FIREARM.
3 (2) IF THE COURT DETERMINES THAT THE RESPONDENT IS LIKELY TO
4 ENDANGER OR CAUSE PHYSICAL INJURY TO THE RESPONDENT OR ANOTHER IF THE
5 RESPONDENT HAS ACCESS TO A FIREARM, THE COURT SHALL ORDER THE
6 RESPONDENT:
7 (I) TO SURRENDER TO LAW ENFORCEMENT AUTHORITIES ANY
8 FIREARM IN THE RESPONDENT’S POSSESSION; AND
9 (II) NOT TO PURCHASE OR POSSESS ANY FIREARM FOR THE
10 DURATION OF THE ORDER REQUIRING THE RESPONDENT TO COMPLY WITH
11 ASSISTED OUTPATIENT TREATMENT.
12 (C) (1) IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE PROVISIONS OF § 1–203 OF THE
13 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE, ON APPLICATION BY A STATE’S ATTORNEY OR A
14 LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER WITH PROBABLE CAUSE TO BELIEVE THAT A
15 RESPONDENT WHO IS SUBJECT TO AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION POSSESSES A
16 FIREARM AND FAILED TO SURRENDER THE FIREARM, A COURT MAY ISSUE A SEARCH
17 WARRANT FOR THE REMOVAL OF THE FIREARM AT ANY LOCATION IDENTIFIED IN
18 THE APPLICATION FOR THE WARRANT.
19 (2) (I) A COURT MAY ENFORCE AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION
20 THROUGH ITS CONTEMPT POWERS.
21 (II) THE COURT MAY IMPOSE ANY REASONABLE SANCTION FOR
22 A VIOLATION OF ITS ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
23 (D) AN ORDER UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION SHALL EXPIRE
24 WHEN THE RESPONDENT IS NO LONGER SUBJECT TO AN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH
25 ASSISTED OUTPATIENT TREATMENT UNDER § 10–6A–08 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
26 (E) IF A RESPONDENT SURRENDERS A FIREARM UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF
27 THIS SECTION, A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER SHALL:
28 (1) PROVIDE TO THE RESPONDENT INFORMATION ON THE PROCESS
29 FOR RETAKING POSSESSION OF THE FIREARM; AND
30 (2) TRANSPORT AND STORE THE FIREARM IN A PROTECTIVE CASE, IF
31 ONE IS AVAILABLE, AND IN A MANNER INTENDED TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO THE
32 FIREARM DURING THE TIME THE ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION IS IN EFFECT.

4 HOUSE BILL 1306
1 (F) THE RESPONDENT MAY RETAKE POSSESSION OF A SURRENDERED
2 FIREARM AT THE EXPIRATION OF THE COURT’S ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION,
3 UNLESS THE RESPONDENT IS NOT OTHERWISE LEGALLY ENTITLED TO OWN OR
4 POSSESS THE FIREARM.
5 (G) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER LAW, A RESPONDENT MAY TRANSPORT
6 A FIREARM IF THE RESPONDENT IS CARRYING AN ORDER ISSUED UNDER THIS
7 SECTION AND:
8 (1) THE FIREARM IS UNLOADED;
9 (2) THE RESPONDENT HAS NOTIFIED THE LAW ENFORCEMENT UNIT,
10 BARRACKS, OR STATION THAT THE FIREARM IS BEING TRANSPORTED IN
11 ACCORDANCE WITH THE COURT’S ORDER; AND
12 (3) THE RESPONDENT TRANSPORTS THE FIREARM DIRECTLY TO THE
13 LAW ENFORCEMENT UNIT, BARRACKS, OR STATION.
14 (H) (1) A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER WHO TAKES POSSESSION OF A
15 FIREARM IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL, AT THE
16 TIME THE FIREARM OR AMMUNITION IS SURRENDERED OR SEIZED:
17 (I) ISSUE A RECEIPT IDENTIFYING, BY MAKE, MODEL, AND
18 SERIAL NUMBER, ALL FIREARMS THAT HAVE BEEN SURRENDERED OR SEIZED;
19 (II) PROVIDE A COPY OF THE RECEIPT TO THE RESPONDENT;
20 (III) RETAIN A COPY OF THE RECEIPT; AND
21 (IV) PROVIDE INFORMATION TO THE RESPONDENT ON THE
22 PROCESS FOR RETAKING POSSESSION OF THE FIREARMS ON THE EXPIRATION OF
23 THE ORDER.
24 (2) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL TRANSPORT AND STORE
25 ANY FIREARM SURRENDERED OR SEIZED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN ORDER UNDER
26 THIS SECTION:
27 (I) IN A PROTECTIVE CASE, IF ONE IS AVAILABLE; AND
28 (II) IN A MANNER INTENDED TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO THE
29 FIREARM DURING THE TIME THE ORDER IS IN EFFECT.

HOUSE BILL 1306 5
1 (3) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY MAY NOT PLACE ANY MARK ON A
2 SEIZED OR SURRENDERED FIREARM FOR IDENTIFICATION OR OTHER PURPOSES.
3 (4) (I) ON EXPIRATION OR TERMINATION OF AN ORDER UNDER
4 THIS SECTION, A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY THAT HOLDS A FIREARM
5 SURRENDERED OR SEIZED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ORDER SHALL NOTIFY THE
6 RESPONDENT THAT THE RESPONDENT MAY REQUEST THE RETURN OF THE
7 FIREARM.
8 (II) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN A FIREARM
9 TO A RESPONDENT ONLY AFTER THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY VERIFIES THAT
10 THE RESPONDENT IS NOT OTHERWISE PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING THE
11 FIREARM.
12 (III) SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, ON
13 REQUEST OF THE RESPONDENT, A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN ALL
14 FIREARMS BELONGING TO THE RESPONDENT NOT LATER THAN 48 HOURS AFTER
15 THE EXPIRATION OF AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
16 (5) (I) A RESPONDENT WHO DOES NOT WISH TO RECOVER A
17 FIREARM OR AMMUNITION SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN
18 ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION OR WHO IS PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING FIREARMS
19 UNDER TITLE 5 OF THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE MAY:
20 1. SELL OR TRANSFER TITLE TO THE FIREARM TO:
21 A. A LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER; OR
22 B. ANOTHER INDIVIDUAL WHO IS NOT PROHIBITED
23 FROM POSSESSING THE FIREARM UNDER FEDERAL OR STATE LAW AND WHO DOES
24 NOT LIVE IN THE SAME RESIDENCE AS THE RESPONDENT; OR
25 2. REQUEST THE DESTRUCTION OF THE FIREARM.
26 (II) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL TRANSFER
27 POSSESSION OF A FIREARM OR AMMUNITION TO A LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER OR
28 AN INDIVIDUAL DESCRIBED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (I)1B OF THIS PARAGRAPH ONLY
29 AFTER:
30 1. THE LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER OR INDIVIDUAL
31 PROVIDES WRITTEN PROOF THAT THE RESPONDENT HAS AGREED TO TRANSFER THE
32 FIREARM TO THE DEALER OR INDIVIDUAL; AND

6 HOUSE BILL 1306
1 2. THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY VERIFIES THE
2 AGREEMENT WITH THE RESPONDENT.
3 (III) ON REQUEST OF THE RESPONDENT, A LAW ENFORCEMENT
4 AGENCY MAY DESTROY FIREARMS SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH
5 AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
6 (6) IF AN INDIVIDUAL OTHER THAN THE RESPONDENT CLAIMS
7 OWNERSHIP OF A FIREARM SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN
8 ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION, THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN THE
9 FIREARM TO THE INDIVIDUAL IF:
10 (I) THE INDIVIDUAL PROVIDES PROOF OF OWNERSHIP OF THE
11 FIREARM; AND
12 (II) THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY DETERMINES THAT THE
13 INDIVIDUAL IS NOT PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING THE FIREARM OR AMMUNITION.
14 (7) IF A FIREARM IS NOT RECLAIMED WITHIN 6 MONTHS AFTER THE
15 PROVISION OF NOTICE TO A RESPONDENT UNDER PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS
16 SUBSECTION:
17 (I) NO PARTY SHALL HAVE THE RIGHT TO ASSERT OWNERSHIP
18 OF THE FIREARM; AND
19 (II) THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY HOLDING THE FIREARM
20 MAY DESTROY THE FIREARM.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
22 October 1, 2026. It shall remain effective until the taking effect of the termination provision
23 specified in Section 3 of Chapter 704 of the Acts of the General Assembly of 2024. If that
24 termination provision takes effect, this Act shall be abrogated and of no further force and
25 effect. This Act may not be interpreted to have any effect on that termination provision.

